content: Tomorrow marks the 25th anniversary of the week Los Angeles burned. The 1992 riots spanned five days, left 50 dead, 2,000 injured and over one billion dollars in damages. Inside Tolliver's Barbershop on Florence Ave, just a few blocks from where the chaos broke out, South LA native William Taylor holds the harrowing photos he captured during the 1992 Riots. He says many people often miss an important detail when they look back at that time. "A lot of people think the Riots started when Rodney King got beat. People didn't start rioting until after those four officers were acquitted."
name: S I M O N E

content: Lt. Michael Carodine worked a 24-hour shift the night the Riots broke out. As a native of South LA, the Riots didn't just hit close to home -- they hit his home. He holds back tears as he recalls his experience but says it's therapeutic to talk about it all these years later. . "I was in the midst of it. Did I get shot at? Yes. Did I have to shoot at people? Yes. And I hurt some people -- not because I wanted to, but because I had to. You had folks that were shooting firefighters trying to put out fires. But the one thing that stands out after all these years? I watched my community burn. It was a community that I had a responsibility to police and it still burned. That took a lot out of me in so many respects. I felt helpless. Whether I was a police officer or not, that was my community and I watched it burn."
name: S I M O N E

content: (3 of 3) "My first reaction was I completely understand why people are upset. That night Rodney King got beat there were some serious failures. A lot of cops -- black and white -- were upset. People saw it for what it was. And understanding the history of police and community relations in South LA, I knew exactly why people were pissed off. At the same time, I wanted to think our people are better than that. We were reacting the same way "they" wanted us to -- and by "they" I mean the folks that didn't like us anyways. There are a lot of things that law enforcement still needs to do to ensure we are viewed as part of the community. Our department has done a phenomenal job in the years since trying to rebuild that trust. But in order for people to have the kind of relationship they want with us, they have to reach out to us as well. I'll ask people have you joined a Community Advisory Board? Are you part of Neighborhood Watch? Have you ever gone to a Citizen's Police Academy? What are you doing to reach back out and say okay, I see what you're doing let me do my part too." -- Lt. Michael Carodine, LAPD

content: SHEILA!!!! This is my Mom's essence in a photo, captured sometime in the 90's at our old home in Eagle Rock. If you've ever been to our home you already know -- you will never forget my mom's hospitality! Her smile *literally* sparkles and her joy is just infectious. She is kind, warm, so full of life and God's love. She makes everyone feel safe, comfortable and welcome. I get my creative mind from this woman and a bit of her theatrics may have rubbed off on me too üòÇ Having two headstrong young women in one home made for lots of drama, but to any moms and daughters going through it right now -- push through. You'll meet again as adults and reach a whole new understanding of each other. @moneesmom you are my rock, my hero, my inspiration and my motivation. The world would be a better place if I could become a little more like you everyday ‚ú®
